European inflation slipped into food
The accelerating inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the skyrocketing food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording annual inflation of 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, the Luxembourg-based Union Statistical Office announced.
Official forecasts put the probability at only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, did not cut the basic interest rate, on the pretext that the decrease, together with rising commodity prices and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause an inflation spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we have to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation in Germany, at 3.3 percent, broke the twelve-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area soared as a result of soaring food and energy prices.
Wheat futures increased by 88 percent and soybean futures reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, vegetable oil and dairy products had to pay much more in 2007.
The price of crude oil on the world market has risen this year by 52 percent, with the price of black gold reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent, while in 2009 it will already fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by early December support for the Young Democrats Alliance rose significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while the Gallup never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - for the Socialists.
The difference in the case of the Socialist electors for the parties - due to the greater firmness of the electors for the opposition - would mean support for more than two thirds (71%) compared to support for a fifth for the Socialists (20%).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary scans: their support within the totality of the population is two percent.
Among the confident voters there is one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low point - it has never been so high, 41 percent of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the more hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about the change in their own economic situation.
As for the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to worsen and only a tenth expects an improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, higher than any previous Gallup poll, felt that the Prime Minister is doing more badly than good.
Ferenc Gyurcsány is trusted or trusted by 13 percent of those polled, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of those polled.
54% of the population do not trust the Head of Government at all and 27% do not trust the President of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced against the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
Whereas after the October riots last year 35% thought it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, this proportion is now only 20%, with a relative majority (33%) believing that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question on participation answered that they would certainly participate and another 20 percent said they were likely to participate.
In comparison, only 55% of the population would be confident in participating in "a general election to be held this Sunday" and another 15% believe it likely.
74% of the population would disapprove of paying for tuition fees, 79% for medical consultations and 84% for hospital treatment.
If we look at these proportions only among the insured participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of the voters would reject the introduction of tuition fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has increased its prices fivefold
The average price increase of 16% was maintained by the hypermarkets in the Budaörs gold trade triangle, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the commercial golden triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets was registered a growth much higher than one thousand HUF.
As in December last year had already "disappeared" prices in the supermarkets of food, so did not experience a drastic increase in price percentage compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously scary for consumers that what they could buy last year for far less than HUF 9 000, they cannot do today for even HUF 10 000.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF by a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10 573 HUF.
(in 2003 this basket was worth HUF 6800.)
The price of Unicum liqueur and fish remained almost at the same level as in the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in the price of turkey breast, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data from the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to below HUF 200.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with two-liter redemptible bottle cost less than HUF 200, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only HUF 257.
However, in Napi Auchan's basket, she was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15%, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18% the prices listed in Napi's basket.
Comparing the values of last year's most expensive basket with that of this year's cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was HUF 1480 per year.
Last year the average price increase was HUF 1206, so that during Christmas last year the VAT increase was felt in the prices.
It was this process that destroyed commerce, the supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price range to be applied to each product and to calculate the effect of price changes on consumption.
(If the trader plans the speed of circulation of a product poorly, he may lose a significant profit on the margin adjusted to the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive basket was HUF 1720 higher than the value recorded in 2006, while the difference in the cheapest basket was only HUF 844.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price now has been HUF 1630 more than last year and the lowest price also increased by HUF 1284.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic increase in prices in less than 20 months, with the price of basic consumer goods rising by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Statistical Office: this office, in the case of some basic foodstuffs, recorded over the 12 month period a price increase of more than 30 per cent.
So for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to Napi's basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product which was quite expensive last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case, only a 10 per cent increase in prices.
The Commission has also been asked to provide a report on the situation in the Community, which will be published in the Official Journal of the European Union.
The hypermarkets don't complain in the golden commercial triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
In our experience, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy large quantities of all products, carrying along preserved food on pallets.
On Wednesday morning, the three stores were lined up in front of the checkout boxes because the number of customers had suddenly increased.
However, we have information that sales volumes are lower within the country, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals, you save money on disinfectants.
This year, several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowded beds and staff overload do not help control infections, says the chief doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals, even disinfectants are being used sparingly.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
A man hospitalized after a serious accident was found to have antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred at this same hospital earlier this year.
A man who was injured in a serious car accident was discharged from hospital and the same patient had to return to hospital shortly afterwards as a result of MRSA infection and since then no major surgery has been possible because of the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, chief of department of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that hospitals have certainly recorded this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents, but no other information is available.
Nearly two thirds of infections (683 cases) are caused by MRSA, or methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any illness.
Infections caused by SA (e. g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once over- or mis-applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become highly antibiotic-resistant and spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, for example wound infections or septicemia in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with weakened bodies, in the elderly or in people with low body weight.
In the opinion of the chief physician of the János Hospital there is nothing special about the infection of MRSA, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff attend them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the appropriate antibiotics for their treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are screened for MRSA in advance, but even this cannot prevent infection in all cases.
It's not in fashion to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital conditions are not conducive to the prevention of formation and contagion with the multidrug-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine inpatients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA in their system.
However, microbiological sampling is not a trend in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections already occur visible in the patient", said the head doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict guidelines for the use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for the treatment of infections and diseases.
It is important to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in outpatients or in basic care", said Karolina Böröcz.
It saves on the disinfectants.
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Handwashing, the use of rubber gloves and masks therefore play a very important role, but there are also considerable shortcomings in this respect in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital wards are often crowded, beds often close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least five feet [1.5 m].
Unfortunately, it can also be seen - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with less favourable economic conditions, disinfectants are used sparingly, there are few nurses and many patients, and therefore there is a greater likelihood of infection.
Karolina Böröcz believes that where appropriate prevention measures are in place, fewer such infections are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The programme seems to be successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol test for police chief who caused a fatal accident.
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the police commander of the XXII district.
It can be ruled out that the dismissed district police commander of the XXII district was driving drunk or in a daze, who on Tuesday hit and killed a passerby - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Attorney General of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary alcohol test which had already established that the former police commander had not consumed any alcoholic beverage before getting behind the wheel.
The then chief of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle when turning to Kossuth Lajos street of the XXII district hit a man of 55 years, who wanted to cross the street, but not in the designated area for pedestrians.
(This last fact, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code is not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way to the bending.)
The bystander died after being hospitalized.
The district police chief resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is in charge of the Budapest Investigative Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander had cooperated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation from the beginning.
€400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian Minister of Finance, János Veres, and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), Marta Gajecka, signed in Budapest on Friday three credit-limit agreements totalling 400 million euros to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, which will be carried out from the Cohesion Fund grant, for which the parties had already previously signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million loan agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this Hungarian objective, the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided upon later, when extending the loan agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euro for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
The talks also covered the construction of the fourth line of the Metro.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalized the details of the Metro financing with the EU, they would again address the issue of whether or not to amend the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this could take place as early as the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary, worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is EURIBOR-compliant and the EIB offers a grace period of eight years, with no commission for keeping the loan at the debtor's disposal.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that Balkan country just mentioned.
What, where and who are buying in the EU's still cheaper market, which will soon become more expensive?
The Bulgarian division of Re/Max was analysed.
The preferred destination for property acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments on the ski slopes and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while Albena beaches, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later the central part of the country - like Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will also attract the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy properties in the especially cheap Rus area.
The capital Sofia can also be attractive, with commercial and office spaces promising a quick return on investment.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golfing paradises in Europe, and can thus be a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
So, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
Analysts believe that those who buy property in Bulgaria are also striving to change their lives and their way of life.
Most of the customers are British, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present and traditionally there are many Russian clients on the Black Sea beaches and in skiing paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in bad condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, and they value the proximity of a large city, shops and generally a local doctor.
The second category is comprised of chalet buyers (Bulgaria was in the top 10 holiday destinations for Germans in December).
The third group consists of real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital-based real estate is rising steadily, as demand is increasing.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, over the last five years, real estate prices have increased by 21 percent annually.
The increase in real estate prices considerably outstrips the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Six Hundred Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at expert level will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration, the negotiations at minister level on the post-2012 international climate regime will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period, set out in the Kyoto Protocol, which runs until 2012.
There are now lively discussions on this subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate precise figures at the moment, although it is inclined to agree that emissions of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 25 to 40 per cent by 2020 compared with 1990.
Another big issue at the conference is whether or not the industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries that need it.
The Council also agreed on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be run by a 16-member board of directors, likely from the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes "Piac és Profit".
The six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister said that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent below 1990 levels by 2020 regardless of whether the 'post-2012 agreement' is signed and is ready to commit to reducing even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibilities and capabilities.
The Commission is also proposing to extend the existing EU-wide system of taxation to include the taxation of small and medium-sized enterprises.
The Hungarian commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared with the period between 1985 and 1987, which our country will comply with, says the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali, where the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed in two years' time, otherwise its entry into force will be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce emissions made in the Kyoto Protocol will not be immediately followed by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN's international scientific association dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and prevent an increase of more than 2°C in the average temperature of the Earth, which, according to scientists, would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British army is recruiting on YouTube
British Army units in a video distributor post footage of action filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
The British air force (RAD) was the first to take advantage of YouTube services: Special units deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are monitored at the Kandahar general operations corps, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers that have been uploaded to the Internet in this way and their "channel" has already been viewed by over 75 thousand people.
The UK Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true purpose of the British Army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs next to nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - but it inevitably has a political message, as it justifies the government's military actions in a specific way.
The Americans have prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the recordings that have been carefully edited and censored, amateur videos, for example about the death of soldiers, also appear in the distributor: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers talk about losses at most, without presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
Moreover, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos of actual operations have already been uploaded to the Internet, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form of recruitment with free-to-download shooter games called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put themselves directly in the place of the soldiers.
