The forces of the giant strike are gathering
The League Unions and the National Federation of Workers Committees will form a strike committee on Friday to coordinate the strike on Monday which will last indefinitely.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while on Monday - the day on which the final vote on the public health law will be held - the work stoppage will begin.
This action will certainly cause great difficulties in transport, since rail traffic will be completely stopped and until 1 p.m. the workers of the Budapest Public Transport Company will also be on strike.
On Friday afternoon the League Unions will inform about the details of their strike on Monday which they will hold together with the National Federation of Workers Commissions.
The strike committee of the LIGA and the National Union of Machinists will also be formed to coordinate the actions on Monday.
On Saturday there will be a protest rally, while on Monday the participating unions will go on strike for an indefinite period, if an agreement is not reached with the government.
That is to say, on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law, they did not inform the date of the end of the strike.
If the National Assembly disapprove the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their call for a strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
Based on the agenda of the National Assembly on Monday, it is also possible that the public health law will only be voted on in the very late hours of the night, or at best close to midnight.
As a result of the strike which will begin on Monday, there will be significant difficulties in transport: the railways will be closed indefinitely, and in the morning part of Budapest's public transport and more than half of the inter-city bus transport of the Volán companies may be stopped.
At the same time, in many parts of the country, half of the roads will be closed.
Numerous unions and civil society organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League's Web page.
Some unions announced their strike for an indefinite period, others for a definite period.
Until Thursday afternoon, the State Railroad and the Free Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) could not reach an agreement even on the minimum services, although, as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are traveling on trains.
According to information received so far, from the beginning of the day until 1 pm, the workers of the Budapest Collective Transport Company will be on strike, the Budapest Airports from 7 to 9 am, will hold a four-hour strike, the LIGA Electrical and Thermal Industry Unions, the Teachers' Unions called for a strike of 2 and the Democratic Teachers' Union from 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Medical Association will be calling a national strike at alternate times and the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers (SDTSSS) which is part of the Forum of Trade Union Cooperation, will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal for public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is that the new way of calculating pensions, which will come into force next year, be introduced gradually.
The third is that they should ensure, even before 2010, that, in the case of early retirement, the occupations which deserve it can enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) which is part of the League Unions, do not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway sidings and expect another different proposal.
Political Capital: In the country the risk is increased by the Hungarian Guard
According to the Risk Analysing Division of the Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was formed in August this year with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The company's 'risk warning' states that the greatest political risk in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity is the fact that 'with the aggravation of the existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary, even in the short term violent ethnic clashes may occur'.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to be the provocation of an event of this nature, the representative of the research institute added.
They said that this was due to one of the main failings of the main actors of Hungarian political life: "the main actors of public life gave the public debate on the Roma problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on the existing discrepancies between Roma and Hungarians".
This aggravates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, empowers extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflict - they estimate.
In addition to that, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly deteriorated Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of the stability and democratic development of the country".
They remind us that: from the autumn of 2006 the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary received increasing publicity and momentum and that since the summer of 2007 numerous organizations that call themselves "national self-defense associations" have been established in the country.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the training of their members for defense - even armed - (civil defense, national defense, defense of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, that is, the State" - they add.
They said: all this is done in accordance with the method which tries to give a civil presentation to different political aspirations, based on the discontent of society with politics and with political parties.
The emphasis on civil and associational forms in the case of these associations not only avoids the legal problems of legal registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a risk factor also from the point of view of neighbourhood relations.
"In recent months, in many neighbouring states they referred to the Hungarian Guard as a potential danger, while ultra-nationalist political figures in certain neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy with the creation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this has an influence on the political stability of the region' they added.
The establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, according to the Institute of Investigation, and political risks have increased throughout the region.
