In Hungary the law defines precisely the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and it has already become a widespread practice that around the public holidays - which next year will be fewer - the working days are reorganized.
Even in the EU or in North America, holidays are not uniform.
The Hungarian laws make a distinction between national holidays, state holidays and public holidays.
The holidays are fundamentally related to religious and historical holidays.
Let us celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are holidays - the latter especially so that those who have spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven festivals written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on 15 March in memory of the revolution of 1848 and on 23 October, the day commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1 the holiday of labor, on November 1 and 2 we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, in our country there are two-day festivals: Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Depending on the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it is often a bridge when there is only one working day before or after the holiday.
In exchange for the extended weekends, the Saturdays before the weekends cannot be missed from work or school.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when work is to be done exactly in exchange for the day immediately preceding or following the holiday.
This legal provision is binding on all employers and their employees, as well as on employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory for service companies and institutions which, because of their function, work continuously even during the public holidays.
This year the work schedule can only be altered around the end of the year holidays: from 24 December onwards, life in the country practically stops, since according to experience, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year, many of our holidays will coincide with weekends or weekdays, so there will be fewer changes in working hours than this year.
First, the agenda will be modified around the work holiday so that then, for four successive days, the workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2nd will be a holiday.
The other change is related to the holiday of 23 October: on Saturday 18 October, work will be required instead of Friday 24th.
On the other hand, next year during the end-of-year holiday you will be able to rest, since from December 24 onwards you will not work anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
