Banks want to solve the crisis
The American Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
More than $100 billion will be received in the money market through bidding.
In these auctions banks auction the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will send out forty billion dollars to bid, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step should solve the biggest economic problem, namely the continuing growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend", wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his client report.
"This coordinated action by central banks likely reduced the U.S. recession from 65 percent to 50 percent", Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Economists are still expecting billions in losses.
"Central banks should really be afraid of what they have yet to do when they decided to take this step", said ABN Amro's chief economist Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad", he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems of access to loans and that they will have to lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks decided to do so after they failed to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for lending money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend money even when the US, Canadian and British central banks cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another fall in interest rates", Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the move by central banks contributes to igniting the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem that is the slump in the US housing market.
