A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen Nazi files, which describe the fate of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not until now only available for 'humanitarian' purposes, that is to say individually and by name, at the request of a former victim or his beneficiaries.
The eleven states responsible for its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the ratification process of this agreement by all the States has been completed, the opening is effective from yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow for research "particularly on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of concentration camps or of detention orders issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find deported or forced labourers and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees at Bad Arolsen handle tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents", declared Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Centre on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
