In parallel to the parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated into the draft in the Senate, the Government has submitted to public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the objective that both enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members of Parliament and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulation in order to guarantee the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the activity of entities so that markets can operate efficiently.
The MiFID, which amends the Securities Market Act, modernises financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors in the European Union.
The new rules will allow financial advisory services to be provided to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firms (FSI), financial advisory firms (FAs), which will be joined by securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
It also extends the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments, so that the regulated secondary markets are joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems, which will compete with the current stock exchange operators.
The Act also obliges investment firms to disclose to the market information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management practices and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they carry out, to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
In its passage through the Committee on the Economy of the Congress, several amendments were incorporated, among which it is noteworthy that secured debts are considered as a "complex" financial instrument given their high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated with what happened with the debt of high-risk American mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to define the legal boundaries of the functions that graduates in economics and business can perform 30 years after the Royal Decree of 1977 delimiting the professional functions reserved for economists.
The Senate, for its part, incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as the mediator, who will work for someone else, will not require authorization from the CNMV and will be able to provide its services of product marketing and customer acquisition to different investment companies at the same time.
