What insurance is good for me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver against possible accidents, is a major expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or use of it, among others.
Having the car is just the beginning.
The fact is, choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the vehicle model.
First of all, we must be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is embodied in an insurance contract, which provides that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is set taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, the age of the car, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use given to it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so the greater the likelihood of an accident, the higher the premium.
That is why both men and women over 25 have to pay lower premiums, since statistics show that they have a lower accident rate because of their prudence.
Also, using the figures, the companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will influence the frequency and thus the likelihood of any mishaps.
The higher the frequency, the higher the odds.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium rate.
Therefore, the driver should study the situation carefully to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
The most important variables for choosing one or the other type of insurance are explained here, so that it not only adapts to the characteristics of the insured person, but also offers him a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 face various difficulties in obtaining affordable insurance, such as limited driving experience and old driving licences.
Although all-risk insurance is the ideal way to be well insured, there are other, more economical options.
More cautious drivers can opt for a deductible all-risk policy, so that they get the coverage of a full-risk policy but at a more feasible price.
This type of agreement would involve the customer paying part of the amount of the loss.
"The part of the loss amount that the customer contributes will be pre-established depending on the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount", says Luis Noguera, chief executive officer in Spain of First Europa, an online insurance broker.
Another option is extended third-party insurance, so that the customer is protected against damage caused to third parties, but not against damage caused to his own car.
Plus, you'd be covered for theft, fire and loss of vehicle.
A word of advice.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus and may reduce the cost of the insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate that the company has.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on that basic rate.
"Bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and its profit.
If the company has had a good year it can afford to increase the bonuses", Noguera explains.
After 25 years of age, drivers have an easier time buying insurance, since the accident rate is reduced by the accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is advisable to contract an all-risk franchise.
"Normally young people cannot make use of the experience they have acquired in the past when it comes to accidents, or even driving", says the Spanish director of the European company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, after the 'fear of the novice' has passed.
However, if the client is married but has no children yet, it is preferable to negotiate an all-risk insurance, as long as his financial situation allows it, of course.
The insurance companies consider married couples with children to be the public with the lowest number of claims, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case, the best insurance would be a fully-funded one (which could be 300 euros) or, if there is a high level of premium, a third-party one extended from the third year of the vehicle's life.
"They drive more leisurely and have more purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchise", says Luis Noguera.
For retired people, a full-risk insurance with a deductible (of EUR 150) or an extended third party insurance is recommended if the premium is high.
Car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver against possible accidents, but also because it represents a major expense.
