New fears over gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk that it will affect Russia's export of fuel to Western Europe.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is routed through Ukraine, so every touch between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit fees.
A previous dispute last year cut supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, monopoly gas owner Gazprom, trying to agree on how much money Ukraine should pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom has said it will charge Ukraine more, as it has committed to paying an extra 50% in 2008 for gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could be that Ukraine pays 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit during the talks", Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"Changes in gas prices should not relate to our arguments about the levels of transit rates [to Western Europe] via Ukraine".
The last big gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU's supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supply with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian nations.
NHS "must test foreign workers"
Scotland's NHS needs to check the criminal records of employees from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
The recommendation by Auditor General Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was found to be linked to the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no idea exactly how many foreign staff it has.
However, its report noted other controls that are carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The Auditor General checked the number of foreign staff hired outside the European Economic Area, following the attacks at Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep into the gates of the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, charged in connection with the alleged UK car bombings.
NHS expects to carry out pre-employment checks on candidates to ensure they meet the qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although the health board of Scotland uses "Disclosure Scotland" to carry out criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Britain.
The Auditor-General's report recommends, among other measures, that boards should have the Criminal Records Bureau's guidance, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
"Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these checks, this is not a routine review", the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available on the number of foreign staff in the NHS".
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is", he explained.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreigners, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying which employees have indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures set by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being widely followed.
This includes passport controls, work permits and qualifications checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the policy and guidance for pre-employment of foreigners in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon states: "I had a great interest in this work being carried out in the wake of the Glasgow airport terrorist attack.
He said that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this would be reflected in the updating of the pre-employment screening guidelines for all work groups - including foreigners - which they planned to publish next month.
