Venus's climate may give a glimpse into Earth's future
Venus may once have been a suitable place for life, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit showed the planet more like an Earth twin than had previously been observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus into a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is sufficient to melt lead and is eroded by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The results from the European Space Agency's Venus Express, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a glimpse of how Earth could develop catastrophic changes due to climate.
Professor Fred Taylor, of the University of Oxford Physics Department and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, states: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, when they are two planets so similar.
"Our new data make it possible to construct a scenario in which Venus began as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago".
