Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to sink into; but he still emerges
As political scandals continue in England, this one is not particularly interesting.
There's no sign of any influence swaps, or exorbitant hotel bills in Paris, or extramarital finger-sucking.
But it has been revealed that a wealthy businessman has disguised contributions to the British Labour Party of more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) for nearly four years using false names, and that the party did not report him.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister avoided calling an election, stupidly insulting British intelligence by declaring that opinion polls did not influence his decision, the hope was that he would provide a strong and efficient government.
But instead, like Vince Calbe, the liberal Democrat leads with increasing wit, because the dreaded Mr. Brown has gone from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The bailout of Northern Rock, a struggling bank, demonstrated regulatory weakness and poor judgment in times of crisis.
Bad proposals to change the tax code has put business groups, together, against the government.
The tax authority lost 25 million pieces of personal data that revealed an unimaginable administrative blunder.
A trio of retired generals started a riot in the House of Lords, protesting against cuts in military spending: being ministers of the armed forces is, they claimed, a part-time job.
Now it's the multiple donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour general secretary (and former accomplice) has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is walking irrevocably towards the exit.
Governments can reach a tipping point after they find themselves unable to govern.
People don't believe them as politicians, but they usually suspend their disbelief when a new pack takes control.
Once it is clear that the prime minister cannot improve things, that he does not have much time left, that suspension is too much: public officials start failing; cabinet ministers expose themselves; the press seeks out bad news; and the government gets defensive and does not focus.
On the one hand, Brown's position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders he cannot defend himself by arguing that he is new.
As much as I'd like to disown Tony Blair, he was his superior lieutenant.
The Northern Rock issues and the authority registration tax are related to the decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he isn't directly involved in the Blairish backlash - or "partner cash", the investigation into political party funding - voters may assume he is.
However, Mr. Brown's situation is not as bad as it seems.
The plates are not as bad as the Tories want to make out.
As in Mr. Bean, no one has died, nor been directly conned.
And the remedy, though painful, is to give what Mr. Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable and brutal government.
The new political donation scandal is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, who compares his donations to charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
This may be so, but the decision is not his.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who is buying access to those in power.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew about Mr. Abraham's deal, and that it was not illegal, will obviously be facing Jon Mendlesohn, the fundraising manager who was asked about the donations in October.
But Mr. Brown is so far not implicated: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these actions, though the bulk of the payments were made after he took control of the office in June.
So far the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He's been quick to condemn his party for breaking the law, but he's been slow to make decisions on a family matter, a commission of inquiry into the matter - led, to a large extent, by a judge and a bishop.
In this case, the morals are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it's a police matter.
In addition, there are other things Mr Brown should do, such as finding a permanent and independent head for the Committee on Standards in Public Life, as he has not had one for six months, and he should also press for genuine party financing reform.
This will require hard co-operative labour with the Tories, and perhaps a renunciation of the special financial position with the unions - bitter measures for a partisan like Mr Brown.
But he must face some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a good level of support in the polls; he has two years to win voters; and the only way he can move to victory is by acting with impeccable probity and solid competition.
