Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's natural for some dorsal fins to swim excitedly around.
Now that the U.S. housing market is in crisis, predators have their sights set on the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of infection are already visible.
There is an increase in both card charges and delinquency rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been amortized or that are more than 30 days overdue respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 million charge on its American consumer finance business, in part due to weakness in cardholders.
It's too early to panic, though.
Default and crime are at low levels.
According to Moody's, a rating agency, the third quarter delinquency rate of 3.89% was almost a percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the US Bankruptcy Code (2005) led to a sharp drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; the number of filings (and thus defaults) would be growing again, or it may be that conditions for borrowers were worsening.
The industry also reports robust payment rates, which show how much of their debt is paid by consumers each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is fairly strong, despite the paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emissions volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of crisis infection between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge credit card debts now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at cash flow than assets, so falling prices don't necessarily trigger a change in borrowers' creditworthiness.
They can even work to give the emitters an edge.
The incentives for consumers to continue to pay off the mortgage decreases if the properties are worth less than the loan value; and as a result, paying off the card debt falls down the list of priorities.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions of mortgage lenders, by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That should in theory reduce the risk of a quick asset recall.
"We're not going to wake up one day and reevaluate all the loans", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer of Capital One.
If a sudden infestation of subprime in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If home prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a harsher future.
We need to keep an eye on those dorsal fins.
British bankers found guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who went on trial for their responsibility in the fraud with the former head of Enron's financial office, Andrew Fastow, were found guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew were originally found not guilty of seven counts of fraud for colluding with Fastow in a secret financial operation in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of employees.
