Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron company controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of a myriad of frauds at Enron, which helped its downward spiral into bankruptcy.
In 2002, the bank valued the subsidiary's interests at zero, but the three Brits knew it would value up.
A company under Kopper's control bought the bank interest in the subsidiary for $1 million.
