But the 20 million was in the hands of the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers collected $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others received about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow was found guilty of two counts of conspiracy in the Enron collapse.
The trio of British men were arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a 6-year sentence in a Louisiana federal prison.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence at Texarkana.
Each of the three British bankers must pay the $1 million they required to live in the United States while the trial was held.
Enron, one of the seven largest companies in the nation, declared bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting trickery, could not hide its millions in debt or make its failing businesses look successful.
