Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere being unsuitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that had not been considered until now. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and eddies in the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that there might be rays on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, the rays are shooting from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud to another, says Cris Russell of the University of California at Los Angeles in the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous Urey-Miller model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
Venus is not like that: if life ever existed there, it would have to be in one of the earliest stages of evolution", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, life cannot exist on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Venus is possibly an evil twin to Earth, but it's still a twin", Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in mass and size, has evolved so differently.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest results of the research, which will be presented in many articles in Nature, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System, but also the fact that it is the only planet in the solar system that has a planet.
"This also shows that the neighbouring planets have more in common with Earth than we had assumed", reports ESA.
Despite the known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers have also discovered a more rapidly rotating cloud vortex at the South Pole.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high Earth atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost as large with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometres.
This planet, also called the morning star or evening star, orbits the sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus is equal to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus, with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar, is not very similar to Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under the same conditions.
On both planets, water had been accumulated that on Earth stayed in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated in the universe.
Whereas on Earth carbon dioxide had turned into carbon rocks, Venus formed most of the atmosphere.
