It's not the wooden boxes.
Anyone who associates the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but doesn't think of Andy Warhol.
Or did you?
At present, the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like a shadow that weighs on the list of works of Warhol.
Most of the ninety-four "type" Glitter-Boxes on this list are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the Moderna Museet in Stockholm conducted internal research and came to disappointing conclusions: the six Brillo-Boxes that the museum's former director Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet are fakes, and almost a hundred of the other "Stockholm-type" paintings that are in circulation on the international art market are also fakes.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confused relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted the wooden boxes red, blue and white, with the same sample that had cartons of soap powder "Brillo".
According to Warhol, in the 1968 exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet museum, hundreds of Brillo-cardboard boxes were on display. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expense), but were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but examples (which were only objects) on display.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed a few Brillo-boxes to be produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Modern Museet.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as original "Stockholm-type" "Brillo-Boxes" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions, some of them were bought for over $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous museum director Pontus Hultén made false statements that in the year 1968 in Sweden were produced and exhibited almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in fact, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the museum's Moderna Museet conservators, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three private Swedish owned that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. First their tight plates were printed and smelted and then painted in oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed plates.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", says Lars Nittve, the director of the Moderna Museet museum and adds that if the "Andy Warhol Art" Authentication Commission in New York does not reach a conclusion, the Moderna Museet museum will classify these six boxes as the copies/exhibits".
In July, the authentication committee formally announced that it accepted these "grave accusations" in the case of soap-dust boxes.
But from that moment on there was absolute silence.
